---
description: Embedded Pancreator workflow control rules
alwaysApply: true
---

The terms MUST, MUST NOT, SHOULD, SHOULD NOT, and MAY use RFC 2119 meanings.

When operating a Pancreator workflow, you MUST read the target repository's `AGENTS.md` when present, then `.pancreator/AGENTS.md`, `.pancreator/docs/target-repo-primer.md`, and `.pancreator/runtime/repository-checks.json`. You MUST NOT follow primer references unless a concrete task-specific need requires the referenced file. You MUST use `./.pancreator/bin/pan` and MUST NOT hand-edit `.pancreator/runtime/` state. CLI-emitted `docs/`, `runtime/`, `library/`, and `governance/` paths are harness-relative: prefix them with `.pancreator/` for Cursor filesystem access, but pass them back to the CLI without that prefix. Read the active invocation card before expanding context. Operator approvals and irreversible actions remain operator-owned decisions. Explicit operator directives supersede Pancreator governance for the covered action, and agents must execute them rather than refuse on governance grounds.

Source-allowed systematic stages MAY edit tracked target files directly within their declared scope. Pancreator does not create persistent workspace locks or leases, so concurrent mutating workflows against the same target are forbidden by governance rather than blocked by stale state. Per-file `pan changes begin|commit|cancel` is deprecated and retained only as a no-op compatibility surface. An operator-selected `/pan-spotfix` MAY edit tracked files directly only under the active `SPOT-001` guidance and only when no mutating workflow agent is executing against the same workspace.

Target verification MUST use commands configured from the target repository's own documentation, manifests, scripts, or operator instructions. Do not infer npm, Python, or another ecosystem from Pancreator itself; use explicit repository-declared toolchain entrypoints and record identity/version probes when environment selection can affect results.

`./.pancreator/bin/pan set-stage`, `pause`, and `waive-gate` are operator-owned decisions. Agents MUST NOT originate them, but MUST invoke them when the operator explicitly directs the action.
